description: From Middle English fen, fenne, from Old English fenn (“fen; marsh; mud; dirt”), Proto-West Germanic *fani, from Proto-Germanic *fanją (compare West Frisian fean, Dutch veen, German Fenn, Norwegian fen), from Proto-Indo-European *pen- (“bog, mire”). Compare Middle Irish en (“water”), enach (“swamp”), Old Prussian pannean (“peat-bog”),  Sanskrit पङ्क (paṅka, “marsh, mud, mire, slough”).

entries.meaning: A type of wetland fed by ground water and runoff, containing peat below the waterline, characteristically alkaline.
examples: Milton! thou shouldst be living at this hour:
England hath need of thee: she is a fen

entries.meaning: A unit of currency in China, one-hundredth of a yuan.

description: From fan, by analogy with men as the plural of man.

entries.meaning: (dated, fandom slang) Fans; a plural form used by enthusiasts of science fiction, fantasy, and anime, partly from whimsy and partly to distinguish themselves from fans of sport, etc.

description: From Middle English *vene, Kentish variant of *fine, from Old English fyne (“moisture, mold, mildew”), from Proto-Germanic *funiz, *fun- (“moisture, mold”); compare vinew.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) A kind of mildew that grows on hops.
